    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/biotransformation-rule-encoding/000",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "BAM operates by applying biotransformation rules to known \"anchor\" molecules, which exhibit high spectral similarity to unknown spectra, thereby hypothesizing and ranking potential structures for the corresponding \"suspect\" molecule... These rules, drawn from extensive biochemical databases like RetroRules and KEGG, encapsulate the promiscuous behavior of enzymes toward substrates.",
      "asbval:note": "The paper describes BAM's core function of applying biotransformation rules from KEGG and RetroRules to generate candidate structures, matching the research question.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1021-acs-analchem-4c01565",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "biotransformation-rule-encoding",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "research_question",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "This skill encodes reaction biotransformation rules from metabolic databases (KEGG, RetroRules) into operator representations that enable systematic generation of candidate molecular structures from input metabolites.",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T14:10:06.022683+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/biotransformation-rule-encoding/001",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "BAM's application to the global molecular network signals an important step forward in metabolomics, enabling discovery and annotation of novel analog molecules in a data-driven fashion... BAM's methodology, which harnesses vast public MS/MS data and biotransformation rules, paves the way for deeper insights into metabolic processes and significantly enriches the field of metabolite annotation.",
      "asbval:note": "The paper demonstrates BAM's scalability to hundreds of millions of spectra and its role in exhaustively applying biotransformation rules for large-scale annotation.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1021-acs-analchem-4c01565",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "biotransformation-rule-encoding",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "research_question",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "It is essential for scaling molecular structure discovery in untargeted metabolomics when the space of plausible biotransformations must be exhaustively represented.",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T14:10:06.022683+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/biotransformation-rule-encoding/002",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "To extract and apply these rules, we employed PROXIMAL2. This tool aligns each reactant\u2013product pair using a maximum common substructure algorithm to identify the reaction center, and then creates a lookup table entry defining the changes at the reaction center and its neighbors... BAM systematically employs these rules to generate and rank potential molecular structures (\"derivatives\") for the \"suspect\" molecule\u2014the unknown compound associated with the query spectrum. To do so, BAM makes use of PROXIMAL2 to apply the biotransformation rules to the anchor molecule, identifying suitable reaction centers for the proposed structural changes.",
      "asbval:note": "PROXIMAL2 is explicitly used for biotransformation rule extraction and application in BAM.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1021-acs-analchem-4c01565",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "biotransformation-rule-encoding",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "tools",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "PROXIMAL2 - Prerequisite tool for biotransformation rule extraction and metabolic pathway prediction; BAM integrates PROXIMAL2 operators to encode biotransformation rules",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T14:10:06.022683+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/biotransformation-rule-encoding/003",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "Next, the graph neural network-based GNN-SOM tool is used to predict the site-of-metabolism and rank these putative derivatives based on the likelihood of each atom being a reaction center... For this, we use GNN-SOM, a tool that employs a graph neural network to predict the likelihood of each atom in a molecule being the target of a biotransformation operation.",
      "asbval:note": "GNN-SOM is explicitly used for site-of-metabolism prediction and ranking derivatives in BAM.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1021-acs-analchem-4c01565",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "biotransformation-rule-encoding",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "tools",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "GNN-SOM - Graph neural network tool used alongside BAM for site-of-metabolism prediction and enzymatic product ranking; supports biotransformation rule application",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T14:10:06.022683+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/biotransformation-rule-encoding/004",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "BAM was implemented using two different code environments. First, PROXIMAL2 was applied and its results were analyzed using Python 3.9, PubChemPy (version 1.0.4), BioServices (version 1.11.2), scikit-learn (version 1.1.2), NumPy (version 1.23.2), NetworkX (version 2.5), RDKit (version 2022.03.5), KCF-Convoy (version 0.0.5), Pandas (version 1.4.3), Matplotlib (version 3.5.3), and Seaborn (version 0.12.2).",
      "asbval:note": "RDKit is listed as a software dependency for BAM implementation.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1021-acs-analchem-4c01565",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "biotransformation-rule-encoding",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "tools",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "RDKit - Chemical informatics library for parsing, validating, and manipulating SMILES structures during biotransformation rule encoding",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
