      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/chemical-structure-deduplication/002",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "BAM was implemented using two different code environments... All code, examples files, and detailed instructions are available as open source under the MIT license at https://github.com/HassounLab/BAM.",
      "asbval:note": "BAM is confirmed as the framework implementing biotransformation rule application. However, the paper does not explicitly describe a 'structure deduplication' step as part of BAM's pipeline. BAM's three documented steps are: (1) anchor identification, (2) biotransformation rule application via PROXIMAL2, and (3) ranking via GNN-SOM. Deduplication is not mentioned as an explicit BAM component.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1021-acs-analchem-4c01565",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "partial",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "chemical-structure-deduplication",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "tools",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "HassounLab/BAM framework implementing biotransformation rule application and structure deduplication as part of the full molecular structure discovery pipeline",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000361"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T14:10:19.309884+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000339"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/chemical-structure-deduplication/003",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "Multiple candidates can be generated for each anchor\u2013suspect pair because biotransformation rules might be applied to different atoms in the anchor molecule or because multiple rules match the observed precursor mass difference.",
      "asbval:note": "Paper confirms that multiple candidates can be generated from the same anchor via different rule applications or different reaction centers. However, it does not explicitly address whether the same transformed structure can result from multiple pathways, nor does it describe a deduplication mechanism to handle this scenario.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1021-acs-analchem-4c01565",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "partial",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "chemical-structure-deduplication",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "scope",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "After applying biotransformation rules to generate candidate product structures from input molecules, when the same transformed structure can be produced via multiple transformation pathways or rule applications",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000361"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T14:10:19.309884+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000339"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/chemical-structure-deduplication/004",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "BAM successfully generated the correct suspect structure in 4171 cases, achieving a recall of 24.2% when a derivative is generated... BAM demonstrated impressive accuracy in ranking the correct derivatives, achieving an average rank of 2.1 and ranking the correct suspect first in 57.7% of cases",
      "asbval:note": "Paper demonstrates that BAM produces ranked candidate structures for annotation, but does not explicitly describe deduplication as a mechanism to ensure non-redundancy. The ranking step (via GNN-SOM) prioritizes candidates but does not eliminate duplicates.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1021-acs-analchem-4c01565",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "partial",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "chemical-structure-deduplication",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "scope",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "Ensures a non-redundant candidate pool for downstream molecular structure annotation in untargeted metabolomics",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000361"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T14:10:19.309884+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000339"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/mass-spectral-feature-grouping/000",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "Molecular networking uses spectral alignment via modified cosine similarity to visualize spectra and any corresponding annotations as a network, which enables additional interpretation of query spectra. The global molecular network was recently constructed from 521 million MS/MS spectra... From these nodes, we identified paired annotated compounds with high spectral similarity (modified cosine similarity above 0.8).",
      "asbval:note": "Paper uses molecular networking with modified cosine similarity threshold (0.8) to construct networks, but the primary task of BAM is not graph-based clustering to identify connected components. Instead, BAM uses the precomputed global molecular network to identify anchor-suspect pairs and applies biotransformation rules for structure prediction. The card conflates molecular networking (network construction) with BAM's actual workflow (biotransformation-based annotation). BAM does not perform de novo clustering; it leverages existing network edges.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1021-acs-analchem-4c01565",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "partial",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "mass-spectral-feature-grouping",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "research_question",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "Group MS features into molecular families by constructing a similarity network from MS/MS spectral data, filtering edges by similarity threshold, and applying graph-based clustering to identify connected components.",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000361"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T14:10:32.923109+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000339"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/mass-spectral-feature-grouping/001",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "To address this problem, we have developed the Biotransformation-based Annotation Method (BAM)... BAM operates by identifying and applying biotransformation rules to an 'anchor' molecule\u2014a known compound whose MS/MS spectrum exhibits high similarity to a given query spectrum.",
      "asbval:note": "BAM does implement biotransformation-based annotation and uses the global molecular network, but BAM does not construct the molecular network itself\u2014it reuses a precomputed global molecular network. The paper states: 'As a more efficient alternative, we utilized a precomputed molecular network, which we refer to as the global molecular network.' BAM's role is annotation via biotransformation rules applied to anchor-suspect pairs identified from the network, not network construction or feature grouping per se.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1021-acs-analchem-4c01565",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "partial",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "mass-spectral-feature-grouping",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "tools",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "BAM - Implements the complete biotransformation-based annotation workflow including global molecular networking for feature grouping and structure discovery",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000361"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T14:10:32.923109+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000339"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/mass-spectral-feature-grouping/002",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "To extract and apply these rules, we employed PROXIMAL2. This tool aligns each reactant\u2013product pair using a maximum common substructure algorithm to identify the reaction center, and then creates a lookup table entry defining the changes at the reaction center and its neighbors... Finally, for a given anchor\u2013suspect pair, BAM applies the rules whose mass difference matches the observed precursor mass difference between the anchor and suspect to generate candidate derivatives for the query molecule.",
      "asbval:note": null,
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1021-acs-analchem-4c01565",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "mass-spectral-feature-grouping",
