      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/metabolite-structure-annotation-integration/000",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "BAM leverages the principle that reactant and products of biochemical reactions often share molecular substructures, leading to high spectral similarity. This spectral similarity, when analyzed within a biological context, provides a more biologically relevant and comprehensive approach to annotation compared to traditional methods that rely solely on spectral similarity. BAM operates by identifying and applying biotransformation rules to an 'anchor' molecule\u2014a known compound whose MS/MS spectrum exhibits high similarity to a given query spectrum.",
      "asbval:note": "The paper describes BAM's core function of integrating biotransformation rules with spectral similarity (molecular networking) for annotation. The research question accurately captures the paper's main contribution.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1021-acs-analchem-4c01565",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "metabolite-structure-annotation-integration",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "research_question",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "Integrate biotransformation-predicted candidate structures with global molecular networking to annotate untargeted metabolomics features and assign them to molecular families.",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T14:10:46.056972+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/metabolite-structure-annotation-integration/001",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "To address this problem, we have developed the Biotransformation-based Annotation Method (BAM). At its core, BAM leverages the principle that reactant and products of biochemical reactions often share molecular substructures, leading to high spectral similarity.",
      "asbval:note": "BAM is confirmed as the primary tool. The paper explicitly describes it as an end-to-end method integrating biotransformation rules with molecular networking.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1021-acs-analchem-4c01565",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "metabolite-structure-annotation-integration",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "tools",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "BAM - End-to-end pipeline for biotransformation-based annotation and global molecular networking integration",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T14:10:46.056972+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/metabolite-structure-annotation-integration/002",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "To extract and apply these rules, we employed PROXIMAL2. This tool aligns each reactant\u2013product pair using a maximum common substructure algorithm to identify the reaction center, and then creates a lookup table entry defining the changes at the reaction center and its neighbors.",
      "asbval:note": "PROXIMAL2 is confirmed as used within BAM for applying biotransformation rules to generate candidate structures.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1021-acs-analchem-4c01565",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "metabolite-structure-annotation-integration",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "tools",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "PROXIMAL2 - Generates biotransformation rules and candidate transformed structures from parent metabolites and reaction databases",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T14:10:46.056972+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/metabolite-structure-annotation-integration/003",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "Next, the graph neural network-based GNN-SOM tool is used to predict the site-of-metabolism and rank these putative derivatives based on the likelihood of each atom being a reaction center. For this, we use GNN-SOM, a tool that employs a graph neural network to predict the likelihood of each atom in a molecule being the target of a biotransformation operation.",
      "asbval:note": "GNN-SOM is confirmed as used within BAM for ranking candidate structures by predicting site-of-metabolism.",
