    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/metabolite-structure-annotation-integration/005",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "BAM operates by identifying and applying biotransformation rules to an 'anchor' molecule\u2014a known compound whose MS/MS spectrum exhibits high similarity to a given query spectrum. These rules, drawn from extensive biochemical databases like RetroRules and KEGG, encapsulate the promiscuous behavior of enzymes toward substrates. BAM systematically employs these rules to generate and rank potential molecular structures ('derivatives') for the 'suspect' molecule\u2014the unknown compound associated with the query spectrum.",
      "asbval:note": "The scope description aligns with BAM's workflow: starting with biotransformation rules applied to anchor molecules, generating candidate structures for unknown (suspect) molecules, and using spectral similarity networks.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1021-acs-analchem-4c01565",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "metabolite-structure-annotation-integration",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "scope - When to use",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "You have a set of candidate transformed structures generated by biotransformation rules (e.g., from a parent metabolite and enzymatic reaction rules), paired with untargeted LC-MS/MS data (MS1 precursor masses and MS/MS spectra), and you need to assign each detected feature to a ",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T14:10:46.056972+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/metabolite-structure-annotation-integration/006",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "Although untargeted mass spectrometry-based metabolomics is crucial for understanding life's molecular underpinnings, its effectiveness is hampered by low annotation rates of the generated tandem mass spectra. To address this issue, we introduce a novel data-driven approach, Biotransformation-based Annotation Method (BAM), that leverages molecular structural similarities inherent in biochemical reactions.",
      "asbval:note": "BAM is designed for untargeted metabolomics with low annotation rates, implying it is not intended for already-annotated features.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1021-acs-analchem-4c01565",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "metabolite-structure-annotation-integration",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "scope - When NOT to use",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "Input features are already annotated to known reference standards \u2014 use targeted approaches instead.",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T14:10:46.056972+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/metabolite-structure-annotation-integration/007",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "BAM operates by identifying and applying biotransformation rules to an 'anchor' molecule\u2014a known compound whose MS/MS spectrum exhibits high similarity to a given query spectrum. These rules, drawn from extensive biochemical databases like RetroRules and KEGG, encapsulate the promiscuous behavior of enzymes toward substrates.",
      "asbval:note": "BAM fundamentally requires biotransformation rules and anchor molecules; without these, the method cannot function.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1021-acs-analchem-4c01565",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "metabolite-structure-annotation-integration",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "scope - When NOT to use",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "No biotransformation rules or parent structure anchors are available for the dataset.",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T14:10:46.056972+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/metabolite-structure-annotation-integration/008",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "For a given query MS/MS spectrum, BAM identifies an annotated spectrum associated with an anchor molecule that closely resembles the query spectrum in terms of spectral similarity, a process which we conceptually refer to as 'anchor search'.",
      "asbval:note": "The paper confirms that BAM requires MS/MS spectral data for similarity computation, but does not explicitly state a minimum peak threshold. The claim about '<4 significant peaks' is not directly supported by the passages.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1021-acs-analchem-4c01565",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "partial",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "metabolite-structure-annotation-integration",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "scope - When NOT to use",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "MS/MS spectral data are not available or are of insufficient quality for similarity computation (e.g., <4 significant peaks per spectrum).",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000361"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T14:10:46.056972+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000339"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/molecular-network-clustering-and-analysis/000",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "BAM operates by identifying and applying biotransformation rules to an \"anchor\" molecule\u2014a known compound whose MS/MS spectrum exhibits high similarity to a given query spectrum... BAM systematically employs these rules to generate and rank potential molecular structures (\"derivatives\") for the \"suspect\" molecule",
      "asbval:note": "Paper describes BAM using a precomputed global molecular network (constructed via molecular networking with modified cosine similarity) to identify anchor-suspect pairs, then applying biotransformation rules to generate and rank candidate structures. The card claims BAM 'constructs spectral similarity networks' and 'applies graph-based clustering,' but the paper states BAM 'reused the existing global molecular network' rather than constructing it de novo. BAM does not perform clustering; it identifies anchor-suspect pairs from a pre-existing network. The biotransformation rule application and ranking are confirmed.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1021-acs-analchem-4c01565",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "partial",
