    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/molecular-network-construction-for-metabolomics/001",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "Next, the graph neural network-based GNN-SOM tool is used to predict the site-of-metabolism and rank these putative derivatives based on the likelihood of each atom being a reaction center. GNN-SOM,12 a tool that employs a graph neural network to predict the likelihood of each atom in a molecule being the target of a biotransformation operation.",
      "asbval:note": "GNN-SOM is explicitly named and used for ranking candidate structures and predicting site-of-metabolism.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1021-acs-analchem-4c01565",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "molecular-network-construction-for-metabolomics",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "tools",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "GNN-SOM",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T14:11:19.464748+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/molecular-network-construction-for-metabolomics/002",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "To do so, BAM makes use of PROXIMAL211 to apply the biotransformation rules to the anchor molecule, identifying suitable reaction centers for the proposed structural changes... To extract and apply these rules, we employed PROXIMAL2.11 This tool aligns each reactant\u2013product pair using a maximum common substructure algorithm to identify the reaction center.",
      "asbval:note": "PROXIMAL2 is explicitly named and used to apply biotransformation rules and identify reaction centers.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1021-acs-analchem-4c01565",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "molecular-network-construction-for-metabolomics",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "tools",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "PROXIMAL2",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T14:11:19.464748+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/molecular-network-construction-for-metabolomics/003",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "To address this problem, we have developed the Biotransformation-based Annotation Method (BAM)... BAM consists of three steps (Figure 1): 1.For a given query spectrum, determine an annotated spectrum associated with an anchor molecule based on high spectral similarity. 2.Apply relevant biotransformation rules that match the observed mass difference between the anchor and suspect to generate candidate structures\u2014derivatives\u2014for the query spectrum. 3.Rank the derivatives based on the likelihoods of the applied biotransformation.",
      "asbval:note": "BAM is the primary method orchestrating the entire workflow described in the paper.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1021-acs-analchem-4c01565",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "molecular-network-construction-for-metabolomics",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "tools",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "BAM",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T14:11:19.464748+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/molecular-network-construction-for-metabolomics/004",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "GNN-SOM was trained on enzymatic interactions from the KEGG database to classify each atom within a graph representation of a molecule as the site-of-metabolism for a given enzyme. BAM uses GNN-SOM to rank the generated derivatives based on the likelihood of their corresponding site-of-metabolism.",
      "asbval:note": "The role description matches the paper's use of GNN-SOM for ranking and site-of-metabolism prediction.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1021-acs-analchem-4c01565",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "molecular-network-construction-for-metabolomics",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "tools[GNN-SOM].role",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "Ranks candidate molecular structures and site-of-metabolism predictions for suspects identified in the molecular network, leveraging graph neural networks trained on biotransformation patterns",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T14:11:19.464748+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/molecular-network-construction-for-metabolomics/005",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "This tool aligns each reactant\u2013product pair using a maximum common substructure algorithm to identify the reaction center, and then creates a lookup table entry defining the changes at the reaction center and its neighbors... for a given anchor\u2013suspect pair, BAM applies the rules whose mass difference matches the observed precursor mass difference between the anchor and suspect to generate candidate derivatives for the query molecule.",
      "asbval:note": "PROXIMAL2's role in generating and applying biotransformation rules is accurately described.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1021-acs-analchem-4c01565",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "molecular-network-construction-for-metabolomics",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "tools[PROXIMAL2].role",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "Generates biotransformation operators that define chemical transformations between anchor and suspect pairs, constraining the chemical feasibility of structure candidates",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T14:11:19.464748+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/molecular-network-construction-for-metabolomics/006",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "BAM operates by identifying and applying biotransformation rules to an 'anchor' molecule\u2014a known compound whose MS/MS spectrum exhibits high similarity to a given query spectrum... BAM systematically employs these rules to generate and rank potential molecular structures ('derivatives') for the 'suspect' molecule.",
      "asbval:note": "BAM's orchestrating role is accurately described in the card.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1021-acs-analchem-4c01565",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "molecular-network-construction-for-metabolomics",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "tools[BAM].role",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "Orchestrates end-to-end molecular structure discovery using the constructed network of anchor-suspect pairs combined with biotransformation rules and GNN-SOM ranking",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T14:11:19.464748+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/molecular-network-construction-for-metabolomics/007",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "Although untargeted mass spectrometry-based metabolomics is crucial for understanding life's molecular underpinnings... BAM operates by identifying and applying biotransformation rules to an 'anchor' molecule\u2014a known compound whose MS/MS spectrum exhibits high similarity to a given query spectrum... thereby hypothesizing and ranking potential structures for the corresponding 'suspect' molecule.",
      "asbval:note": "The scope accurately describes the use case: untargeted MS/MS data with anchor compounds used to infer structures of unknown suspects.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1021-acs-analchem-4c01565",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "molecular-network-construction-for-metabolomics",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "scope",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "You have untargeted metabolomics data (e.g., LC-MS/MS spectra) and need to organize compounds by structural relatedness to enable structure discovery for unknown metabolites. Specifically, use this skill when you have anchor compounds with known SMILES/InChI and want to infer str",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T14:11:19.464748+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/parent-product-relationship-tracking/000",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "BAM systematically employs these rules to generate and rank potential molecular structures (\"derivatives\") for the \"suspect\" molecule\u2014the unknown compound associated with the query spectrum. To do so, BAM makes use of PROXIMAL2 to apply the biotransformation rules to the anchor molecule, identifying suitable reaction centers for the proposed structural changes.",
      "asbval:note": "Paper describes generating and ranking derivatives from anchor molecules using biotransformation rules, but does not explicitly discuss 'serializing' or 'maintaining' parent-product relationships as a documented data structure. The paper focuses on generating candidates and ranking them, not on tracking/serializing the transformation pathway as a primary objective. The research question overstates the emphasis on relationship tracking/serialization.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1021-acs-analchem-4c01565",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "partial",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "parent-product-relationship-tracking",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "research_question",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "Maintain and serialize parent\u2013product relationships when applying biotransformation rules to input molecular structures, enabling traceability of how candidate molecules are derived from anchor compounds.",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000361"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T14:11:35.879052+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000339"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/parent-product-relationship-tracking/001",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "BAM was implemented using two different code environments. First, PROXIMAL2 was applied and its results were analyzed using Python 3.9, PubChemPy (version 1.0.4), BioServices (version 1.11.2), scikit-learn (version 1.1.2), NumPy (version 1.23.2), NetworkX (version 2.5), RDKit (version 2022.03.5), KCF-Convoy (version 0.0.5), Pandas (version 1.4.3), Matplotlib (version 3.5.3), and Seaborn (version 0.12.2).",
      "asbval:note": "RDKit is confirmed as part of BAM implementation. Role is consistent with standard RDKit usage in cheminformatics.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1021-acs-analchem-4c01565",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "parent-product-relationship-tracking",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "tools",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "RDKit: Parse, validate, and manipulate SMILES strings; execute biotransformation rule application on molecular structures",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T14:11:35.879052+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/parent-product-relationship-tracking/002",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "To address this problem, we have developed the Biotransformation-based Annotation Method (BAM). At its core, BAM leverages the principle that reactant and products of biochemical reactions often share molecular substructures, leading to high spectral similarity. BAM operates by identifying and applying biotransformation rules to an \"anchor\" molecule\u2014a known compound whose MS/MS spectrum exhibits high similarity to a given query spectrum.",
      "asbval:note": "BAM is confirmed as the method that applies biotransformation rules and generates derivatives. However, the paper does not emphasize 'parent-product relationship tracking' as a primary feature; it emphasizes generation and ranking of candidates. The tool does orchestrate rule application but the explicit tracking/serialization of relationships is not a stated design goal.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1021-acs-analchem-4c01565",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "partial",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "parent-product-relationship-tracking",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "tools",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "HassounLab/BAM: Implement biotransformation rule engine and orchestrate parent\u2013product relationship tracking within the annotation method",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000361"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T14:11:35.879052+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000339"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/parent-product-relationship-tracking/003",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "Next, the graph neural network-based GNN-SOM tool is used to predict the site-of-metabolism and rank these putative derivatives based on the likelihood of each atom being a reaction center. The final step involves ranking the generated candidate structures. For this, we use GNN-SOM, a tool that employs a graph neural network to predict the likelihood of each atom in a molecule being the target of a biotransformation operation.",
      "asbval:note": "GNN-SOM is confirmed to rank candidates by site-of-metabolism likelihood. However, the paper does not describe it as ranking 'by parent-product relationships' explicitly; it ranks by the likelihood of atoms being reaction centers. The ranking is based on transformation plausibility (via KEGG-trained enzyme likelihood), not on explicit parent-product relationship metadata.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1021-acs-analchem-4c01565",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "partial",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "parent-product-relationship-tracking",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "tools",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "HassounLab/GNN-SOM: Predict site-of-metabolism and rank candidate products by their parent\u2013product relationships and transformation plausibility",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000361"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T14:11:35.879052+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000339"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/parent-product-relationship-tracking/004",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "These rules can be sourced from databases like RetroRules, KEGG, or Metacyc. In this case, RetroRules was used due to its sizable collection of biotransformation rules. To extract and apply these rules, we employed PROXIMAL2. Additionally, we utilized RetroRules as the basis for extracting biotransformation rules\u2014yielding 42,307 unique rules\u2014covering a wide range of possible biochemical transformations.",
      "asbval:note": "Both KEGG and RetroRules are confirmed as sources of biotransformation rules. Paper uses RetroRules in the main evaluation.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1021-acs-analchem-4c01565",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "parent-product-relationship-tracking",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "tools",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "KEGG or RetroRules: Provide the biotransformation rules (reaction definitions) applied to generate products from parent structures",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T14:11:35.879052+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/parent-product-relationship-tracking/005",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "BAM operates by identifying and applying biotransformation rules to an \"anchor\" molecule\u2014a known compound whose MS/MS spectrum exhibits high similarity to a given query spectrum. These rules, drawn from extensive biochemical databases like RetroRules and KEGG, encapsulate the promiscuous behavior of enzymes toward substrates. Specifically, they include a molecular substructure specifying a reaction center and the structural changes occurring therein. BAM systematically employs these rules to generate and rank potential molecular structures (\"derivatives\") for the \"suspect\" molecule.",
      "asbval:note": "Paper describes generating derivatives from anchor molecules using biotransformation rules, but does not emphasize 'documenting' or 'serializing' parent-product relationships as a primary use case. The scope overstates the importance of relationship tracking/documentation relative to what the paper actually describes (generation and ranking).",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1021-acs-analchem-4c01565",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "partial",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "parent-product-relationship-tracking",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "scope",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "When you have applied biotransformation rules to generate candidate product structures from a set of input molecules (represented as SMILES strings) and need to document which product structures were derived from which parent structures.",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000361"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T14:11:35.879052+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000339"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/pipeline-end-to-end-execution-and-validation/000",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "BAM was able to assign correct molecular structures to 24.2% of examined anchor-suspect cases, thereby demonstrating remarkable advancement in metabolite annotation.",
      "asbval:note": "Paper explicitly describes BAM execution on validation dataset (60,368 anchor-suspect pairs from global molecular network) and reports performance metrics (24.2% recall, 57.7% top-1 ranking accuracy). Code and data deposited on Zenodo and GitHub.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1021-acs-analchem-4c01565",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "pipeline-end-to-end-execution-and-validation",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "research_question",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "Execute a complete bioinformatics pipeline (BAM) on a validation dataset and compare predicted outputs against reference annotations to assess reproduction of reported metrics.",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T14:11:54.468446+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/pipeline-end-to-end-execution-and-validation/001",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "To extract and apply these rules, we employed PROXIMAL2. This tool aligns each reactant\u2013product pair using a maximum common substructure algorithm to identify the reaction center, and then creates a lookup table entry defining the changes at the reaction center and its neighbors.",
      "asbval:note": "PROXIMAL2 is explicitly used for biotransformation rule application and candidate generation.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1021-acs-analchem-4c01565",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "pipeline-end-to-end-execution-and-validation",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "tools",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "PROXIMAL2 - Dependency for biotransformation operator generation and metabolite pathway prediction",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
